> In a former life (well, about 10 years ago) our Head Chef used to be a lawyer.
> When his firm asked him where he'd like to go on secondment, they were probably
> expecting him to choose Berlin or possibly Munich. His answer? Thailand. Living
> there for three months he used to eat in the food halls with all the locals
> every lunchtime and this became his go-to dish. Stick a fried egg on for extra
> authenticity!

Boil 350ml of water (exactly) with @salt{1/4%tsp} and pour in your @Basmati Rice{1}.
Turn the heat to the lowest setting, place a lid on the #pot{} and leave for ~{10%minutes}.
Take off the heat and leave for another ~{10%minutes}.

> Tip: To make sure your rice is perfect don't touch the lid until 20 mins are up!

Peel and very, very finely dice the @Echalion Shallot{1}(peeled and finely diced)
and the @Garlic Clove{2}(peeled and finely diced). Very finely dice as much of
the @Red Chilli{1}(finely diced) as you dare.

> Tip: If you can mash all these ingredients under the flat of your knife or
> whizz them in a processor all the better for the flavours.

Cut the tops and bottoms off the @Green Beans{1}(tops and bottoms removed and
chopped in half) (this is called 'top and tailing!), then chop them in half.
Heat @oil{2%tbsp} in a pan on high heat. Once hot add the green beans to the pan
and stir fry for ~{2%minutes}. Remove to a #plate{} for later.

Turn the heat down to medium-high and add @oil{1%tbsp} to the pan. Add the
shallot, garlic and chilli with a little @salt{} and cook for just under
~{1%minute}.

Turn the heat back to high, add the @British Pork Mince{250%g} into the pan
and break up with your #wooden spoon{}. Once the pork is cooked through add the
green beans, the @Sweet Soy Sauce{1.5%tbsp} and the @Fish Sauce{1/2%tbsp}. If the
mixture is a little dry add @water{2%tbsp}.

At this point, if you want to go super authentic, then fry an @?egg{1}(fried)
until it's nice and crispy around the edges, with a nice runny yolk to pop on
top of your rice.

Take your pork mixture off the heat and stir through a few tbsp of torn
@Fresh Thai Basil{1/2%bunch}(torn) leaves. Serve with your rice and get stuck
in. Aloy mak! (That's 'super tasty' in Thai!)